So I think I'm fortunate in that all my stakeholders today I'm right half of them I'm actually I would

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:13.120
say I'm friends with so we're very locked in and I understand as they make the decision what's

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:20.240
happening so I do understand when they actually do take an action but I'm not really satisfied

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:24.559
with just knowing that they they took an action what I'm trying to figure out right now and if

00:00:24.559 --> 00:00:31.360
anyone has thoughts on this I'd love to have a conversation later is if you make a prediction

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:36.639
that there is a problem that is going to happen or service level performance is going to deteriorate

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:43.119
that prediction is out there you have stakeholders or operators or whoever that has access to that

00:00:43.119 --> 00:00:48.240
information if you don't know specifically what they're doing right they could be having calls

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:51.599
with people they could be turning dials that you don't even know about in the background

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:58.799
is there a way that over time you can log your historical data right your historical predictions

00:00:58.799 --> 00:01:04.720
and then over time you can look at what actually materialized is there a way and I really think

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:11.360
it's regression modeling to say based upon what we see in these groups where we are predicting

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:20.400
performance deterioration compared to the whole we we can estimate that the predictions are having

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:26.320
the intended effect right I think it's really comparing a few different groups there over time

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:31.519
as long as you are cataloging the predictions you are making can you formulate that into

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:40.959
into a way to quantitatively measure the impact so to answer your question number one in my current

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:44.480
situation I'm so looped in with the stakeholders that yes I know when they are making decisions

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:50.000
number but I don't know how to quantitatively measure it yet which

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.680
leads to number two I'm trying to figure out ways to quantitatively measure it.

